		<span class="username">MI Redeux</span>
	</div>
	
	
		<div class="title">Re: How do you store your backups?</div>
	
	<div class="content">
		<blockquote class="restore"><div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			<div>
				Originally Posted by <strong>Zumino Zufeilon</strong>
				<a href="showthread.php?p=1782980#post1782980" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost.gif" alt="View Post" /></a>
			</div>
			<div class="message">Have an external HDD, a Synology NAS, a Dropbox account, and at least 2 'work backup' flashdrives.<br />
<br />
I'm not paranoid, nosiree</div>
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div>This guy, this guy gets it.  <br />
<br />
I've been burned too many times not to have learned my lesson.  <br />
<br />
All backups all the time with as much redundancy as reasonable has been engrained into my psyche.<br />
<br />
Arq (<a href="http://www.haystacksoftware.com/arq/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.haystacksoftware.com/arq/</a>) is my favorite backup software implementation thus far.  <br />
<br />
Only downside is that it is OS X only, so I can't use it on any of my other systems.  <br />
<br />
It's very well done though.  <br />
<br />
Arq complements time machine exceptionally.<br />
<br />
Tarsnap (<a href="https://www.tarsnap.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://www.tarsnap.com/</a>) is an excellent multi-platform option, however it seems like it will be super expensive and it is a one man shop so very exposed to falling apart if the guy running it dies, seems super nice though (<a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=5767116" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=5767116</a>) and a super nerd.<br />
<br />
I don't use thumb drives anymore as I've been burned too many times when I've lost them, usually whilst on a death march and not paying all that much attention.  <br />
<br />
I use Amazon's Cloud Drive ( <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/feature.html?ie=UTF8&amp;docId=1000796931" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.amazon.com/gp/feature.htm...cId=1000796931</a> ) for moving small files around instead.  <br />
<br />
I was using Dropbox, but they always have some tragic fuck up periodically so I have no confidence in them.  <br />
<br />
Then I tried using Google Drive after that, but I try to avoid Google's products anymore aside from their Open Source software and e-mail.  <br />
<br />
The lack of quality support and fragile state it was in when I last tried it turned me off from the project.  <br />
<br />
Amazon's Cloud Drive has been nice, there isn't a Linux or BSD client though, but since I only use Linux in a VM and have no use for it in the context of BSD that is okay.<br />
<br />
I have all of my most important project related files backed up to github and use git for them as I do all of my projects and papers in Emacs w/ git or a Jetbrains product w/ git.<br />
<br />
I realize now I don't have my servers backed up in any way....  <br />
<br />
That would make for a shitty recovery.</blockquote>
	</div>
